adr_address: Calle de la Reina, 4, 28004 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Calle de la Reina, 4, 28004 Madrid, Spain
name: Angelita Madrid

reviews.text: Excellent time sitting at the bar and chatting it up with the bartender who spoke very good English.  His knowledge of wine were great as were the recommendations.  Would highly recommend this place to anyone traveling by!

We had 4 dishes and all were more than fantastic! Very nice and friendly service. Wanted to come back a few days later but it was completely full - remember to book well in advance especially on weekends.

Amazing cocktails, lounge feel. They map the flavor profile of each drink (intensity, citrus, umami, sweet, etc.) and have a ton of combinations. Also marked which can be alcohol-free, and give popcorn with every drink!

Wonderful place! The meat (I didn't remember a dish) and the cheese plate were sooo delicious! Extra stars for your stuff: guys on a bar were so nice: offered a very tasty drinks and answered on all my questions! Thank you for a delightful time!
Great place for dinner in Madrid. Very good ambience, Good selection of wines and also has a few Vegetarian options...

adr_address: Plaza de Oriente, 2, 28013 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Plaza de Oriente, 2, 28013 Madrid, Spain
name: Café de Oriente Palacio Real

reviews.text: I love this place! Amazing atmosphere, decoration, a lot of interesting details. Have one if the best location. You can stay on terassa and enjoy view of Plaza Oriente or seat inside and be in special atmosphere. All staff are very kind and nice! Have good choice of breakfast, deserts, have good menu. Almost all breakfast served with French fries. Hardly recommend to visit ☕

The staff doesn't speak English although this is in a touristic area. The food is quite expensive, but not very good. We were here with a group of five. The meat was partly raw. I mean raw, not undercooked. It was even still cold. The so called scrambled eggs were not eatable. My colleague returned them after one bite. The only reason for two stars is that the restaurant looks really nice and they play a nice selection of music.

Great location near the Palace, but keep in mind that you can only get the cheaper prix fixe menu if you sit inside.

Restaurant has an old world charm with a good number of locals.  

Food was pretty good...3 course lunch with drink and bread included was 11 Euros per person.

This restaurant has amazing views of the palace. Service appauling. Had to ask for milk with English tea. Dessert came with no crust. Had to ask for forks to eat it with. I've had afternoon tea many times here and introduced many friends. It's not enjoyable anymore.

Disappointed to say the least ... service was just terrible ... took ages and it was rather unpleasant. Food... was average... not a place I would go back to. Maybe it's better in summer when you sit outside. It is also rather pricey.... breakfast for two costs around €30. Nice interior decor but that's the only positive I could say about this place.

adr_address: Calle Eloy Gonzalo, 26, 28010 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Calle Eloy Gonzalo, 26, 28010 Madrid, Spain
name: Sagaretxe

reviews.text: We had an amazing evening! Service was amable and relatively quick for how extremely busy it was! Food was to die for! Tapas sized portions, so we shared some things, and quality was 10/10 😍 terrace was cute right next to a busy street so loads to see! We will be back! Hasta luego!

Delicious pinchos...we had the eggplant, bacalao, 4 cheese and cheesecake for dessert. I enjoyed all of it, the customer service was outstanding. They even offered us free shots... I'd definitely go back, it's well worth a visit.
Lovely. Good food and excellent staff. Thank you!
Nice food here
Great staff, great food.  I have no complaints.

adr_address: Calle Fernando Pessoa, 5, 28027 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Calle Fernando Pessoa, 5, 28027 Madrid, Spain
name: Bar Ruano

reviews.text: Trabajadores de siempre,buen servicio buen precio,un sitio estupendo para desayunar o copita despues del trabajo
Un bar de barrio muy agradable y con la cerveza muy fría
Bar de toda la vida. Bar de barrio...
Bar de barrio, trato cercano y personal muy simpático
Es bastante tranquilo el sitio.

adr_address: Calle de Santa Isabel, 52, 28012 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Calle de Santa Isabel, 52, 28012 Madrid, Spain
name: Museo Nacional Centro de Arte Reina Sofía

reviews.text:
I'm not a major fan of contemporary art,but I still loved visiting Reina Sofia museum. Viewing Guernica in person is a major bucket list item and I wasn't disappointed. There wasn't as much Picasso or Dali paintings as I was expecting.

Note that after 7pm, entry to the museum is free. Doing that gives roughly two hours in the museum, which is not enough. To get free entry, queue up at the ticket office from about 6.30pm and queue in the direction of the exit of the museum complete. Do not queue in the direction of the museum building entrance, else you'll have to re-queue. I saw several people do that.

Give me a thumbs up if that was useful information.

This place is a must-see for whoever likes modern art. The design is by definition modern and makes you think of the Whitney Museum in New York. A lot of things to see (expect at least 4 hours to see everything). Very spacious rooms and not crowded at the end of the day. The bookstore is also nice. And the entrance is free for teachers.

Not impressed. Staff is very rude and the museum has some stupid rules. The guard and two other staff members kept chasing me, because I had a 1.5 litre bottle of water with me. Since when is bringing water with me a problem? Just let me enjoy the art. Needless to say that none of these folks talks english. So I had to return to the cloakroom and leave my water there. Most of the art pieces are cool, there are a few great, that's it. And half the museum was closed when I visited. There is a nice garden, though.

Reina Sofia is a must visit for anyone who likes modern art. Museum's are quite subjective depending on personal preference and I only had a small selection of works I wanted to see so went after 7pm (free entry) which gave 2hrs to see what I wanted. Of course a must see is Picasso's Guarnica which is incredible. There's actually quite a few Picasso works, Dali and Miro so a couple of hours is plenty to see them. If you prefer modern art over classical, do Reina Sofia over Prado.

Very mediocre in my eyes... I’ve been to other modern art museums and was able to appreciate the art there more. At least it was free for students 25 and under...
I also felt very observed; every time we walked into a room they would follow us in. I’ve been to museums with more valuable art and never had that problem.

adr_address: Paseo del Prado, s/n, 28014 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Paseo del Prado, s/n, 28014 Madrid, Spain
name: Museo Nacional del Prado

reviews.text:
The Prado Museum is the beauty of history. The building itself is already inspiring for beauty. It's a shame only that the central entrance is closed. And the main box office and entrance are located from the side.
Truly masterpieces are presented there, the Spaniards in it are presented in all their glory. Velazquez, Goya.
Special attention deserves Bosch Hall. At one time, the Spanish King Philip II loved this artist. And thanks to him, you can now enjoy his most famous paintings in one place.
It is difficult to describe in words, you need to walk in the museum, look and study. And it definitely will take more than one day.

You like Art? You need to go to the Prado. It's massive, you'll need a few hours. Free entry from 6pm till close. Line up early. We lined up at 6pm and had to wait for a good 45 min to get in. That was on a Monday night, can't imagine how long it would take on weekends.

Simply a-m-a-z-i-n-g!!! Soo many masterpieces that you should really divide your visit in a couple of days, to be able to appreciate everything. Or at least start in the morning, when your mind is fresh and your body is energetic. If you don't have enough time you should grab the map provided by the museum and check where the most famous paintings are located. Definitely one of the best museums in the world.

One of the best gallery in Madrid. You can find a lot of  famous paintings there. Entrance is for free just  two hours before closing. The line is very big but so fast. Highly recommended place. Its one of the must visit place in Madrid. Very cool and so atmospheric!

Loved it! I should have paid for the entry ticket then to enjoy the free entry after 6pm. To begin with I had to queue for 50 minutes before I got in at 6.10. By 7.40 the staff showed us out, said the museum is closed. For 1.5 hours, I barely saw 50% of the amazing exhibits.  I will go back to check it out before I leave Madrid. If you are an Art lover, be prepared to spend 2.5 to 3 hours here. But I was surprised that no pictures or videos are allowed inside.

adr_address: Paseo del Prado, 8, 28014 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Paseo del Prado, 8, 28014 Madrid, Spain
name: Thyssen-Bornemisza Museum

reviews.text: I really enjoyed my experience here. They are very friendly here and allow you to photograph everything which I love. They have a temporary exhibition here until June 2019 where there are many religious Christian artworks by some of the top masters including Rubens and Caravaggio. My favorite are Rubens paintings. Some of these paintings give you tingles of energy and beauty watching them. The first floor and a part of the second have modern art and the higher floors have the classical and Baroque paintings and some sculptures as I have seen what I believe is a Rodin there. Highly recommend this place.

Absolutely magnificent. Great private collection of world class art. Buy tickets online and go early to avoid the queues. Nice little cafe/restaurant with good service and cheap food. Start on the second floor and work your way down. Must-see when in Madrid!

It was an amazing experience for me visiting this gorgeous museum. You may find Dutch, German, Italian, Spanish, French , American , Russian and many cultures' artists that may be forgotten especially  in modern art.By the way, the staff in museum shop are so helpful and patient to inform how printing the posters you choose. I bough two and so grateful to have them .pls do not miss out this museum and its shop  in Madrid ..

A wonderful place with various collections. You can easily spend 3 hours there. You can find both temporary and permanent collections. The museum is very modern in its design and brightly colored. Very good location as well (easily accessible). If you're a teacher, the entrance is free.
I mean..its a museum...if you like art go ahead and visit a museum! And this has some very important amazing works. A great way to learn the evolution of art

adr_address: Calle de Fuencarral, 78, 28004 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Calle de Fuencarral, 78, 28004 Madrid, Spain
name: Museo de Historia de Madrid

reviews.text: Excellent. Stumbled across this while walking in the area. Great to learn about the history of Madrid. I'm very grateful it's free. Most other countries in the world charge for everything. Plaza Mayor looks better with trees.

We have wondered by this museum on several different trips and finally went in.  It is free to enter and has a good collection showcasing Madrid's history.  It was a good size, in my opinion.  It wasn't so large that you stop absorbing what you're looking at half way through.  I enjoyed all the maps and vintage photos of Madrid.

Another great museum in a city full of world class museums.  The museum covers the history of the city from the decision to make it a capital and seat of power to current day.  There is a definite focus on the earlier periods but the collection of paintings is very nice for a free museum.  There is also a nice collection of historical maps in the lower level that is worth visiting before you leave.
A surprisingly quiet museum; a fascinating place offering a great wealth of historical knowledge. An interesting oasis of calm in the city.
Very educational. Worth a visit on a rainy day

adr_address: Calle de San Mateo, 13, 28004 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Calle de San Mateo, 13, 28004 Madrid, Spain
name: Museo del Romanticismo

reviews.text: Love this place! You feel like being in a Palace. There is a small shop and also a lovely cafeteria with a small garden. Worth to have a coffee/tea in the garden if weather permits. Highly recommend to everyone!

Nice little museum if about 20+ small rooms. They give you a small guidebook in your language to borrow as you go round. You have to put any bags in a locker before you go in. I went mid-afternoon on a Wednesday and I was practically the only person there.
What a gem! Such a surprise this little museum is now one of my absolute favorites in Madrid. Be sure to explore the streets around the museum for great little restaurants, bars and shops.
Secret place to have a nice coffee in Madrid downtown! Greattttt
Great place with a great collection, pinctures sculptures and so on.

adr_address: Paseo del General Martínez Campos, 37, 28010 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Paseo del General Martínez Campos, 37, 28010 Madrid, Spain
name: Museo Sorolla

reviews.text: Lovely museum in the home of the artist which makes it feel a lot more personal versus a typical museum setting. The house and the garden are both very pretty. It's not expensive at all. Definitely worth visiting.

A wonderful place. Not a mainstream-known painter but very famous in Spain. The layout of the exposition is set like a house just like the painter lived it. You can't do nothing other than appreciate the delicate beauty that sorrounds you.
It takes an hour for the visit if you're on a rush, up to two if you want to taste everything.

Beautiful quiet museum, one of the most underrated in Madrid. Just €3 to see the artist's incredible work and his wonderful home/studio/gardens. Guided tours available, and written guides in several languages also available in each room.

One fine small museum. The residence of Joaquin Sorolla being converted into a museum of many of his impressive works gives further insight into what inspired him. From the ceramics in the patio to the high walls in his studio, going through the exquisitely decorated living and dining room, every inch of the museum breathes the living genius that was Sorolla.
Very nice overview of the painters works. The house is a gem but to my opinion a bit small to do right to all these brilliant paintings and drawings.

vicinity: Paseo del General Martínez Campos, 37, Madrid

adr_address: Calle Ventura Rodríguez, 17, 28008 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Calle Ventura Rodríguez, 17, 28008 Madrid, Spain
name: Museum Cerralbo

reviews.text: A must see in Madrid. Fabulous and slightly eccentric collection. The ballroom is amazing. Go and enjoy. Only complaint is the gardens are always closed when I have been which is a shame. But a truly special place, oh and the stairway....

Interesting mix of a traditional (if you were really wealthy), Spanish house of the time, but with electic mix of museum pieces. Didn't know what to expect, but really enjoyed it and worth the 3 euros entrance fee.

Someone else said if you love palaces & castles you should visit. Absolutely true, it was wonderful & that includes the garden that was open. So very worth an hour or two if visiting Madrid (combine it with the Temple de Debod near by).
Loved this pLace! If you are into palaces, castles and mansions you should go here. Very over the top and amazing.
Fantastic exhibition which by far exceeded my expectation. Don’t even want to recommend to others since it would make this place much popular and crowded!

adr_address: Calle de Serrano, 13, 28001 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Calle de Serrano, 13, 28001 Madrid, Spain
name: National Archaeological Museum

reviews.text:
Absolutely fabulous! Lots to see and learn about civilization in Iberia. Too much too see in one day. You start on the ground floor and move forward in time with each floor. The layout of the floors flows really well.
Not at lot to keep young children interested, so plan accordingly.
The cafeteria is reasonably price, with a good variety if food.
For the €3.00 entry, this place is a steal and worth a visit.

Good museum but the coin section is not very interesting. Also: some important information is missing from a lot of items displayed (such as dates and origins). Otherwise, it is fairly pleasant to wander in the museum. A lot of things to see and you can leave your bags in a locker room before you visit so you feel unencumbered.

Huge museum, huge variety of things to see, it will take you at least 3 hours to see everything. The installations are brand new, it is great for children, and in every room you will find a corner with replicas for blind people to touch. On the ground floor you will find super clean toilets and cabinets where you can leave you belongings. All these for a ticket of 3 euro, and children enter for free. No waiting lines, no crowds.
Quiet during our Friday evening visit. 3 euros for adults, kids free. Nice displays on early humans and the history of coins and money. Educational and interesting.

Quite comprehensive collection, many items are well-explained, the interior light and architecture gives an open feeling to the visitor. Definitely worth visiting, even if you are in Madrid only for 3 days. One suggestion, though: While informing about millenia and humans' development, it would be better to indicate the civilizations that emerged in other parts of the world in parallel to (or much earlier than) those in Iberia. At least a note to remind that 1000 BC was already a highly developed era for other parts of the world, like Egypt, Asia and Middle East; and the timeline there is only for Europe. Looking at the timeline diagram at the entrance, a visitor, without any prior knowledge, might think that the worldwide civil human and sophisticated institutions started in last half of 1st millennium BC, whereas we have the solid phenomena of Sumerians, Egyptians, Hittites, China, India, etc.

adr_address: Av. de los Reyes Católicos, 6, 28040 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Av. de los Reyes Católicos, 6, 28040 Madrid, Spain
name: Museum of the Americas

reviews.text: The museum contains lots of everyday utensils used in the old times in America. Music instruments, knives, weapons, bowls, etc. There are also little models of their house and its surroundings. Also some real life size models of the interiors of their rooms, people and more. It gives you the feel of how people used to live in the lands before occupied by Spaniards.

It has a nice collection, but doesn't quite feel like a major capital city museum representing the Americas. NO ENGLISH whatsoever... A real shame
 So won't give it more then 3 stars

Pretty good collection. You would think Spain would have a really amazing museum of all the incredible things shipped over during the conquest, but sadly a lot of it was lost or ended up on private hands or outside of Spain. If you already knew this then you will enjoy the museum as it does have some great items and is well worth a visit. A lot more gold and silver pre Colombian jewelry and figurines than I saw at the Mexican anthropology museum or the Denver museum. 
Price for non EU citizens was 3 Euros. About 2 hours total will be needed for the 2 floors of permanent collections.

Exhibits are great, inimitable and just interesting. Instruction how go the museum through was okay. Unfortunately I can't give 4-5 stars because even descriptions weren't in English. I had to translate everything I want via phone app.

This is a fantastic spot to learn about the civilizations of the Americas and the Spanish history there. It is geared towards locals instead of tourists. Therefore, all the descriptions are exclusively in Spanish and they don't have too many "wonders" but rather explanatory pieces.

vicinity: Avenida de los Reyes Católicos, 6, Madrid

adr_address: Calle Serrano, 122, 28006 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Calle Serrano, 122, 28006 Madrid, Spain
name: Lázaro Galdiano Museum

reviews.text: this is definitely a museum to visit I loved every artwork in here and this gentleman galdiano he's been a collector of various works of art on oil paintings things out there Leonardo DaVinci Francisco Goya and a whole bunch of different other things but what is noticeable about the artworks did he did collect was that they were all top-notch Best of the Best of the most beautiful things it is definitely wonderful to see something a reflection of a person's dreams and travels and ideas and fusion of beauty at collected in one place and then turn into a museum with his home being visited by so many people lovers of history and people being taught this information not stop because of this definitely worth a visit

Oh my good its fantastic, amazing, its just how could I express my feelings. I'm very excited to be there with all this incredible people enjoing so much I cant tell all the ways haha, Its too much!!!!

reviews.author_name: The Other Side of the Coin
reviews.text: Fantastic little museum with a collection of art and artefacts covering jewellery, painting, sculpture, cloth, table wares and more. Roughly arranged by periods or origins, with occasional contemporary pieces thrown in, which really highlight how bad contemporary art is. Just joking. Kind of. It’s free in the last hour, and the building itself is amazing. Well worth the visit.

Great museum for those interested in various types of art, architecture, history. Under visited but extremely important historical landmark in Madrid. We spent 2 hrs there looking at 4 floors of this collection within this mansion.
Awesome building. Well preserved and the collection is cool too

adr_address: Av. Juan de Herrera, 2, 28040 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Av. Juan de Herrera, 2, 28040 Madrid, Spain
name: Museo del Traje

reviews.text: The permanent collection is full of great peices. After you pass through roughly 400 years of preserved clothing, you get to walk through an interactive exhibit. If you've ever dreamed of wearing special collars or trying on a crinnalen this is the place to come.
Beautiful collection of clothes,  taking you from the earliest tailoring designs to the modern current ones. Worth to be visited!
An intresting museum showing clothes going back from the XVII century. Also, Very intresting historical references to clothing habits of the Spanish.

what an amazing experience. Both men and women, young and old, will enjoy this Museum! The exhibits change, and are absolutely fascinating. You are allowed to take photos, just no flash Photography. They also have very helpful sheets in each room or hallway that explains the time periods and clothing featured. Everything is kept in impeccable condition. It is really a must-see.
Though the exhibition is interesting, the horrible smell of fried food (from museum’s cafe) dominates the entire floor...

adr_address: Calle de Montalbán, 2, 28014 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Calle de Montalbán, 2, 28014 Madrid, Spain
name: Naval Museum of Madrid

reviews.text:
Lots of fun and much larger than one would think.  Has great model ships and wonderful
Details about the various Spanish and Portuguese naval battles.  They even have material going back a couple thousand years.  Really nice job.  Well worth going.  Cool gifts too.
Not too big.  Lots of pictures from Spanish Navy history. Interesting items and things. 20-30 Ship models. Cheap entrance. Good place to spent one hour.

Small but fantastic collection of model ships, weapons, and artifacts from Spain's long maritime history. Well-preserved and in a beautiful building very close to El Prado and other attractions. Only 3 Euro donation for adults.
Small little naval Museum. The exhibits are nice but it would have been nice if the museum was bigger. Took about an hour to go through.
It isn't open totally. Part of it is closed. I was able to enter only small part,but it was astonishing. Consider it as one of the great places to visit in madrid.

adr_address: Paseo de las Delicias, 61, 28045 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Paseo de las Delicias, 61, 28045 Madrid, Spain
name: Railway Museum

reviews.text:
Entrance: 6€, reductions available (kids, students, etc.)
A lot of trains, few big models (whole railways with electricity and running trains) and also hundreds of models of trains.
It was possible to go inside few of those trains.

Too bad it is impossible to go inside more of those.
Also: entrance outside (there were more trains) was closed and prohibited.

Anyway cool to see.

A nice railway museum, not as big as I expected, compared to York Railway museum. Hosts a series of Spanish trains. Unfortunately, it doesn't have the newest generation of fast trains. There is also a model railway.
Everything just in Spanish language. Would be great to understand something, but it looks amazing. The building is an old station which is very authentic for the museum and it looks very nice.

I love the Mercado de Motores at the Museo de Ferrocarril every month. Lots of secondhand sellers outside. Inside is more handmade. Food, clothing, art, textiles, books, housewares. The food trucks outside are very good. Highly recommend. They also have free dog care out front for people who want to leave their dogs while shopping. Love petting all the dogs
Nice place for those interested in railways. There are tiny prototypes for trains from around the globe.

adr_address: Calle de Cervantes, 11, 28014 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Calle de Cervantes, 11, 28014 Madrid, Spain
name: Lope de Vega Museum

reviews.text:
Nice tour with a very knowledgeable guide. If you want to learn not only about Lope de Vega’s life and work but also about life in the 16th century this is a good opportunity. It’s kid’s friendly and not too long so they don’t get bored.
It’s a free tour, but you need to book it in advance because groups are small which I think makes the visit even better.
Definitely recommend.

Don’t miss English guided tour at 4.30 pm. It is worthy to experience authentic atmosphere, hear some interesting stories and see authentic furniture of city people from old times, beyond royalties and clerks. I recommend the museum with chill out garden 😀👍👍👍
Its a free visit, but you have to do a reservation. It was really interesting, out guide was amazing, we had a great time!!
Interesting and very well present ed by the guide.

Interesting history, recommended for people interested in theatre specifically Spanish dramaturgy. Just make sure you reserve a spot to see the full house, otherwise you'll have access to the backyard and a small museum only.

adr_address: Paseo del Prado, 36, 28014 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Paseo del Prado, 36, 28014 Madrid, Spain
name: CaixaForum Madrid

reviews.text:
A cool exhibit featuring some modern art, and even worth stopping by just to see the impressive floral wall!
They have rotating exhibits that can range anywhere from Disney to Opera, so check in advance to see what's new.
Great exhibits. Interesting shop. Nice cafeteria
Always displaying interesting shows or pieces .Happenings happens and it is used as a meeting point !

This museum located in the heart of Madrid offers a continually changing series of exhibitions. It is run by the La Caixa Bank's foundation, so is free if you have one of their accounts. Even if not, it is still very reasonable to enter the building which has been cleverly developed from an existing structure. Due to its location and low price, the fundacion tends to be busy. There is a coffee shop and gift shop selling a range of art books too. Descriptions of the exhibitions tend to be in both Castillian Spanish and in English.
Good exhibition space. Well maintained and subsidised by La Caixa bank foundation. Inexpensive entrance fee and some excellent exhibitions.

adr_address: Plaza de San Andrés, 2, 28005 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Plaza de San Andrés, 2, 28005 Madrid, Spain
name: Museo de San Isidro

reviews.text: Great free museum that is just off a nice sunlit square. Tells the history of Madrid from prehistory. Also some of the stories of San Isidro the patron saint of Madrid.
Wow! I don't understand how this museum doesn't have a perfect rating.  Truly astounding for a small, free museum.
Very interesting place! Clear explanation with english translation
Fascinating museum hidden away. Explores history of Madrid prior to its becoming the capital city. We'll presented and free.
A nice small museum close to the city centre. It has lots of local Roman artefacts and some cool Dino bones!!! Free entrance.

adr_address: Calle de Alcalá, 13, 28014 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Calle de Alcalá, 13, 28014 Madrid, Spain
name: Real Academia de Bellas Artes de San Fernando

reviews.text: A small but interesting collection, a bit of everything. A nice and quiet museum but definitely see the Thyssen collection first.

I'm enjoying my time in the museum of Real Academia de Bellas Artes. Different artworks from classical up to modern. Masterpieces, beautiful paintings, unforgettable sculptures, building and city projects and more more more.  3 floors, please note that without elevator. 8 EUR entrance fee. Highly recommended.

We went on a wednesday when entry is free (check website for details) but would have been well worth the entry on any day. A really good selection of exhibits covering a wide range of periods and types.  Best to allow 3 hrs plus to do it justice.

A delightful second-string very central gallery, you will almost certainly have most of it to yourself! Some nice pieces, the Goya's are definitely the finest things there, and they are really wonderful. I liked the Sorollas, (one of my heroes, and not as well known internationally as he deserves, do go to his house and gallery in Madrid) and a bunch of lovely portraits by someone I have forgotten, but really lovely. Some patchy modern art on the top floor. Worth going, just don't expect the range of masterpieces of the Prado and Thyssen.
There are many good artworks. Worthy of visiting several times.

adr_address: Calle de Ríos Rosas, 23, 28003 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Calle de Ríos Rosas, 23, 28003 Madrid, Spain
name: Museo Geominero

reviews.text: A beautiful museum with a fantastic collection of minerals, fossils and rocks. Your window to earth science history in Madrid. It is free and open to public Monday to Sunday.

Free entrance.
In the beggining it was looking very poorly, but after passing the doors there were hundreds of minerals on 3floors.
Some of them historical with parts of animals. Some simply beautiful.
Nothing in English but still very enjoyable.
Building from the inside is beautiful. Roof and some of the windows are astounding.
Awesome museum!!! Anyone interested in fossils or geology will LOVE this place! And the building is beautiful too
Great museum, full of lovely specimens. The architecture of the main room is mind blowing!

If you like minerals and ancients fossils that is definitely your museum.
Mainly focused on minerals, there are plenty of them on different sizes and shapes. 
The fossils are mostly prehistoric invertebrates  and flora.
The most of them are in glass cabinets and the bigger ones exposed open where you can touch them.

The kids that are studying minerals or like them will have a great time here.

As extra, the historic building deserves by itself a visit, that was designed as headquarters for Geological and Mining Institute of Spain.

The magnificent open main hall with its three stories is great. You can access each of the floors by various metallic and narrow spiral staircases that carries along to the beginning of the 20th century.
In the ground floor the showcases and glass cabinets set up hallways where you can get lost gazing at them.

adr_address: Plaza de Chamberí, s/n, 28010 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Plaza de Chamberí, s/n, 28010 Madrid, Spain
name: Platform 0

reviews.text: Old style metro station made into a museum. Even though I was there almost alone I recieved simple historic information about the place in English. It would be awesome if the info texts were in English too. The visit could take you easily just 10 minutes. They have video playing about history of the station, but only in Spanish.

Free entry and a free tour (or you can self guide). The tour we took was in Spanish, but since we all speak Spanish it was no problem. I thought I heard the tour guide speaking English earlier so it is possible that you can get a tour in English. The tour was very informational and had a ton of great details about the station and the Madrid subway in general. If you understand Spanish, I highly recommend taking the tour. The station is immaculately restored and has a protective barrier between the station and the very active subway tracks. It is a beautiful station. The entrance is very easy to find.

Very interesting museum of one of Madrid's original subway stations. It was a bit of a surprise that trains still come through here, but the station itself is fantastic at showing the history of Madrid's subway network

You can walk through a former metro station which is now closed for public transport. You can also watch a movie about the history of the metro. Unfortunately the movie is only available in Spanish and has no subtitles. Admission is free.

Very cool museum in Madrid. Entry is free and you get to see one of the oldest stations in Madrid that's still on the tracks of line 1. The whole your and information video is in Spanish but very informative. The station itself is very cool as it's been well preserved since the 60's. A must go to attraction in Madrid if you are into metro systems.

adr_address: Calle de José Gutiérrez Abascal, 2, 28006 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Calle de José Gutiérrez Abascal, 2, 28006 Madrid, Spain
name: National Museum of Natural Sciences

reviews.text: A nice environment, quite accessible but not too big. The diversity of elements is quite nice and you're able to see it in around 2-3 hours. There are some projections, but you need to check the time to be able to coordinate your entry. Very nice and varied.
It’s ok, though very dark and I would like more interactive activities for kids

Great little exhibit. Main exhibition has english tags on exhibits and varies from time to time. 2 min walk is the dinosaur and mineral exhibition which you can get to with a general entry ticket. There are no english tags on exhibits at the moment, someone mentioned its planned.

Its small well organised and my 4 year old had solid fun and learned lots in the almost 3 hours there! 

Worth a visit, would not come back soon unless main exhibition changes...and it does :)

Tickets for both of us were a little over 10 euro, well worth the money!
Beautiful museum with good collection of material.....not the most school friendly. Expect 8 students to stay with a monitor or be harassed.
It's a small but nice museum. I enjoyed my tour of the museum. Loved the part on women in science. There's not much to see but still enjoyable with sufficient information on national biology.

vicinity: Calle de José Gutiérrez Abascal, 2, Madrid

adr_address: Calle del Conde Duque, 9, 28015 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Calle del Conde Duque, 9, 28015 Madrid, Spain
name: Museo de Arte Contemporáneo

reviews.text: A total waste of energy walking all the way up there . Huge void with very little if anything in it. The only exhibition we saw was closed and a vacant bearded academic said "maybe it will be open on Wednesday" . It is an amazing space gone to waste ...big huge  voids with nothing to be seen .There were no directions or information on what to see. I'd say see the galleries in Chueca and Reina Sofia plus Reina Sofia extra exhibitions in The Crystal Palace and Retiro Parque. As an art afficiando I would sack the marketing staff and re-employ them selling churros in the Gran Via !
Not that interesting
There isn't very much art. Not easy to navigate. Really a waste of time. There are way better museums in Madrid that are more worth your time.
A very small exhibition...
good place for exibitions

adr_address: Paseo de la Castellana, 214, 28046 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Paseo de la Castellana, 214, 28046 Madrid, Spain
name: Arte Canal Exhibition Center

reviews.text: One of the best exhibition centers in Madrid. Interesting and documented exhibits. I strongly recommend to book tickets online to skip the lines.

This place was quite sobering. When we planned to go here, we didn't realize that it was set up with an Auschwitz historical theme. We hesitated for a moment before going in, but am so glad that we did.

I learned a lot walking through the building and reading all of the different facts. We were in there for about 2 hours, and could have spent another hour if we didn't have somewhere else we had to be. So incredibly informative.

If you are at all interested in human history, this is an absolute must.

The one change that I'd like to see, is to have more dates visible on the walls to give a better perspective on when each thing happened. It was chronologically in order, but including a timeline in each section would have been beneficial.
Saw the Auschwitz exhibition here, well presented in a large space. Easy to get to and well organised.
They have an excellent exhibit about Auschwitz. It's very extensive and extremely well done. Very disturbing but relevant to the worldwide political situation today.  A must-see.
I went to see the exhibit about the Holocausto in Auschwitz and I loved it to know every detail about the stories. Advisable.

adr_address: Calle de Alfonso XII, 68, 28014 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Calle de Alfonso XII, 68, 28014 Madrid, Spain
name: Anthropology Museum

reviews.text: Really impressive exhibition on the Himalayas, polite staff add to a relaxing atmosphere. Regardless of your interest on the stuff around you will find something interesting in every corner. A hidden jewel in the heart of Madrid, made for the smart tourist or local.
One of the only 3 good places of that city... other that those you will find pretty impolite people
Always has really interesting exhibits, customer service is good as well.

If one is very interested in this type of history it is worthwhile going.  However for me it was a bit disappointing. Few items which can be seen within half an hour.  
Entrance 3 euros..... pensionists enter for free.
Some nice pieces, but very little information in English. Not the most spectacular museum one can see. I liked the room dedicated to the founder of the collection (there was info in English there :)

adr_address: Calle del Dr. Esquerdo, 36, 28028 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Calle del Dr. Esquerdo, 36, 28028 Madrid, Spain
name: Museo Casa de la Moneda

reviews.text: This was surprisingly awesome, and the staff were lovely. We ended up going two days in a row - highly recommended (they have audio tours in English too)
free money/coin museum rich and very well designed. good gift shop

The museum dates from the eighteenth century and its origins are closely linked with Tomás Francisco Prieto, General Engraver of the Mint of King Carlos III. He was Director of Engraving at the Royal Academy of Fine Arts of San Fernando and in 1771 founded a School of Engraving. At this school were the craftsmen who would later to work at the Royal Mint of Spain and its colonies.

Very interesting museum. Definitely worth strolling through if you are in the area and have the time.
WARNING: this is NOT the place where "Money Heist" was filmed!
I was looking for the place were La Casa de Papel was shot. It turns out that it's not the building on the tv show but the permanent exhibition is quite interesting.  Worth visiting!

adr_address: A-5, Km. 10,7, 28024 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: A-5, Km. 10,7, 28024 Madrid, Spain
name: Museo del Aire

reviews.text:
They have a large selection of aircraft used in days past and most look like they’ve been taken care of. The museum has aircraft outside and inside in like 6 hangars, all separate but well organized. There are a few space things and instruments used long ago like radar screens on display. 
I recommend using some sunglasses and uv protection since most of the things are outside so come prepared. There is a small gift shop too if you are interested in taking a souvenir with you. The only thing I saw that could help give it a little extra to the place was that maybe they can have actual working simulators for people to use. There are several real simulators obviously not working now but if they could get those running it would be nice.

The display is constantly improved, this year I can see a significant one: Planes have more space around them and you can enjoy 'em better. Pity that three hangars are closed (2, 6, 7 IIRC). Still more than enough to see, admire and enjoy.

Amazing museum!! Great selection of different aircrafts, helicopters etc. Worth to go early in the morning as the museum closes at 2pm. They offer free guided tours however must be booked in advanced over the phone. Highly recommend to everyone, kids and adults!

This is a must for anybody remotely interested in aviation and visiting Madrid. The collection and it's diversity is staggering. It looks like nearly every type flown in the Spanish Air Force has been preserved. The collection is constantly being maintained and painted. The quality is very high and the early pioneers of flight us a great exhibit. There is a shop and this is full of aviation related merchandise. It's free to enter and we gave a donation. It's open from 10:00 till 14:00 and you need to get there early to get the most out of your visit. I want to go back as you can see more is being added.
Spectacular aviation museum....but some of the hangars remain closed if there aren't enough Docents. Truly there are some one-of-a-kind airplanes there.

formatted_address: Plaza de la Almudena, S/N, 28013 Madrid, Spain
name: Museum of Almudena Cathedral

reviews.text: General Admission is 5 dollars if you want to see the insides but if you ask me the exterior is the cool part.
The building on the outside is stunning, worthwhile to go inside and have a closer look, but the amount of people and the line was huge.

price 6,00
sun & hols closed
Amazing cathedral
Worth to see.

vicinity: Plaza de la Almudena, S/N, Madrid

adr_address: Paseo de Recoletos, 41, 28004 Madrid, Spain
formatted_address: Paseo de Recoletos, 41, 28004 Madrid, Spain
name: Museo de Cera

reviews.text: Very good. A huge colection of wax statues from over the world and 2 additional activities for one price. You can receive 2€ discount if you bought city tour bus. Which is also recommended for 1st visit.

Nice place to be during a pair of hours.
PROS: it has been updated with new ideas such as 3D film.
CONS: Some figures are out of date and I'm sure technicials can improve them such as Star Wars, Alien characters that are from 80's.
Price too high (2 adults and 2 children, 70€).
Great place to visit. The statues are very lifelike. The only if is the randomness some of them are displayed (like Yoda on a merry-go-round or spider man close to political figures)
A ridiculous place which made me laugh way more than I expected. It has quality wax figures but sometimes they're so cheesy I can't help but laugh. Love it
Nice place, nice staff, not so big museum.
